 cal > mydate.txt
 date >> mydate.txt
 widjc >> mydate.txt       the errors are not gonna to save into mydate.txt file
 widjc 2>> mydate.txt      to save errors also
 date 2>> mydate.txt       this output is not a error, this output is not gonna save into file mydate.txt
 
 date &>> mydate.txt       it save the output in both ways error or correct.
 
 
 
 ******* Download & Extract files by CLI                              (ls -lh, to show size of file as if 1000byte then 1kb...)
 
      **abc.tar is simillar to abc.zip
      
   ***Creating .tar files:-     tar -czf hey.tar hello.txt             -c :- to create file               hello.txt :- file to tar
                                                                       -z :- convert to zip               hey.tar   :- new tar file
                                                                       -f :- named your tar file
   ***Extract .tar files        tar -xf hey.tar           -x :- extract
                                                          -f :- name of file to extract
      * yes, this cmd can wrote 20cr time the word written in front of yes in only 1 sec.        Ex. yes hello > myfile.txt
      
      
      
               Ex.      mkdir yesfile               --->>  create a dir to work on it
                        yes "I'm Ritik" > hey.txt   --->>  creating a file with text "I'm Ritik" may be 20cr. times by yes cmd
                         ** press "ctrl+c" at just less than 1 sec 
                        ls -lh hey.txt              --->>  check the size of file hey.txt in Mb
                        tar -czf hello.tar hey.txt  --->>  to convert into .tar file
                        rm hey.txt                  --->>  remove the txt file
                        tar -xf hello.tar           --->>  now extract the .tar file
                        
                        
                        
                        
                        
                        
                *****************<<<<<<<<---------User Management--------->>>>>>>>************************
                        
  *** Type of users        1. Super user (root)                user id of root = 0
                           2. System user                      user id of system users = 1 to 999
                           3. Normal/General/Local users       user id of normal users = 1000 +
                           
  *** File to see details of all users :-  /etc/passwd
  
       jack:x:1016:1013:,,,:/home/jack:/bin/bash  ---->>>> username:pass details:Uid:Gid:some info:home dir of user:shell used by user
       
       
       
  *** Type of groups :-    cat /etc/group  --->> command to check all groups 
  
      1. Primary group :- this type of group creates when a user creates.
      2. Secondary group :- this type of groups are created by "groupadd" command
      
  * groupadd groupname              --->>> to create group
  * groupdel groupname              --->>> to delete group without any msg
    delgroup groupname              --->>> to delete group with msg of deleting group
  * usermod -aG groupname username  --->>> to add a user into a group                     |               How r=4, w=2, x=1 for permission
  * deluser username groupname      --->>> to remove user from group                      |   place of r = r__ = 1*2^2 + 0*2^1 + 0*2^0 = 4
                                                                                          |   place of w = _w_ = 0*2^2 + 1*2^1 + 0*2^0 = 2
  ** chown username:groupname filename  ---->>>> to change owner & group of file          |   place of x = __x = 0*2^2 + 0*2^1 + 1*2^0 = 1
   * chown username filename            ---->>>> to change only owner of file             |
   * chown :groupname filename          ---->>>> to change only group of file             |
   
  ** chmod a+rwx a.txt ----->>>> to give all permissions to everyone (owner, group, others)
   
  ** chown -R username:groupname A    ---->>>> to change ownership of A with their childs  (means A k andar sare files or dirs ki ownership bhi change ho jayegi)
  
  ** grep -i hello     ---->>>>>>>     search with case incensitive
                        
                        
                        
                        
                        
                        
                        

